Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Fix #524 and #526: Broken in non-English Thunderbird  A string added in the Firefox 60 fix wasn't copied to the non-English `messages.json` files, which meant that it wasn't in the non-English `strings.properties` and `string.dtd` files. This caused Thunderbird to not load the overlay in Thunderbird, which prevented it from being present in the message window.  To help mitigate this in the future, to some degree, the `i18n.js` script makes sure that all English strings are present in the other languages when creating the the .properties and .dtd files. But I still have to remember to run that script.

Author: Adam Pritchard

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Fix #524 and #526: Broken in non-English Thunderbird  A string added in the Firefox 60 fix wasn't copied to the non-English `messages.json` files, which meant that it wasn't in the non-English `strings.properties` and `string.dtd` files. This caused Thunderbird to not load the overlay in Thunderbird, which prevented it from being present in the message window.  To help mitigate this in the future, to some degree, the `i18n.js` script makes sure that all English strings are present in the other languages when creating the the .properties and .dtd files. But I still have to remember to run that script.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Changed default styles. Generally removed styles and modified spacing. Removed all styles from overall wrapper; this should allow more default mail client styles to be applied, for more consistent looking email. Increased the space between paragraphs a little, to better match Gmail+Chrome's default (double newline) look. Reduced vertical spacing within lists (and especially for sub-lists, which were just wrong). Removed all link styling, so the default will be used. Removed some header and definition list styling that wasn't doing anything anyway. Removed an unused class. Added a background color to table headers.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Make Mozilla preferences handling more robust.  This corrects a few things.  * Fixes issue #237: If a setting got added (directly by the user, or   some other way) that was not a string, errors would repeatedly occur   and spam the console. * Not all preferences were getting synchronized (in particular the   newer ones). * Non-ASCII characters in preferences (for example, in a CSS comment)   would be corrupted when they were retrieved.

Commit Message: remove all uses of XHR; rework getLocalFile  The service worker background doesn't allow XHR reqs, so replace with `fetch`. Also expanded use of `getLocalFile` so that it's used for all(ish) local file requests (rather than sometimes using XHR/fetch).

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: use codecogs for LaTeX rendering by default  Note that the changes in the translation files is mostly just churn. The non-English locales' JSON files weren't properly getting English fallbacks added to them; I did that and sorted the keys on output, to prevent future churn. But the difference in order and whitespace bloated the diff. In the future this shouldn't happen.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Fixed bug: In Firefox (and in Chrome, in theory, but I couldn't make it happen), full-message reverting could fail (instead double-render) if the cursor were outside the rendered block (i.e., at the very beginning, before the wrapper div). This fix involved making full-message render less of a special case: now, if there's no selection, the entire focused element contents are selected. This has a behavioural side-effect that is probably good: It's now impossible to double-render something; if the user renders a portion, and then tries to render the whole, they will instead revert the portion. This may be slightly confusing, but it's better than the destructiveness of double-rendering.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Make Mozilla preferences handling more robust.  This corrects a few things.  * Fixes issue #237: If a setting got added (directly by the user, or   some other way) that was not a string, errors would repeatedly occur   and spam the console. * Not all preferences were getting synchronized (in particular the   newer ones). * Non-ASCII characters in preferences (for example, in a CSS comment)   would be corrupted when they were retrieved.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Fix #524 and #526: Broken in non-English Thunderbird  A string added in the Firefox 60 fix wasn't copied to the non-English `messages.json` files, which meant that it wasn't in the non-English `strings.properties` and `string.dtd` files. This caused Thunderbird to not load the overlay in Thunderbird, which prevented it from being present in the message window.  To help mitigate this in the future, to some degree, the `i18n.js` script makes sure that all English strings are present in the other languages when creating the the .properties and .dtd files. But I still have to remember to run that script.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Fix #524 and #526: Broken in non-English Thunderbird  A string added in the Firefox 60 fix wasn't copied to the non-English `messages.json` files, which meant that it wasn't in the non-English `strings.properties` and `string.dtd` files. This caused Thunderbird to not load the overlay in Thunderbird, which prevented it from being present in the message window.  To help mitigate this in the future, to some degree, the `i18n.js` script makes sure that all English strings are present in the other languages when creating the the .properties and .dtd files. But I still have to remember to run that script.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Fix #524 and #526: Broken in non-English Thunderbird  A string added in the Firefox 60 fix wasn't copied to the non-English `messages.json` files, which meant that it wasn't in the non-English `strings.properties` and `string.dtd` files. This caused Thunderbird to not load the overlay in Thunderbird, which prevented it from being present in the message window.  To help mitigate this in the future, to some degree, the `i18n.js` script makes sure that all English strings are present in the other languages when creating the the .properties and .dtd files. But I still have to remember to run that script.

Commit Message: use codecogs for LaTeX rendering by default  Note that the changes in the translation files is mostly just churn. The non-English locales' JSON files weren't properly getting English fallbacks added to them; I did that and sorted the keys on output, to prevent future churn. To help mitigate this in the future, to some degree, the `i18n.js` script makes sure that all English strings are present in the other languages when creating the the .properties and .dtd files. But I still have to remember to run that script.

Commit Message: use codecogs for LaTeX rendering by default  Note that the changes in the translation files is mostly just churn. Commit Message: use codecogs for LaTeX rendering by default  Note that the changes in the translation files is mostly just churn. Commit Message: use codecogs for LaTeX rendering by default  Note that the changes in the translation files is mostly just churn. Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Fixed bug: In Firefox (and in Chrome, in theory, but I couldn't make it happen), full-message reverting could fail (instead double-render) if the cursor were outside the rendered block (i.e., at the very beginning, before the wrapper div). This fix involved making full-message render less of a special case: now, if there's no selection, the entire focused element contents are selected. This has a behavioural side-effect that is probably good: It's now impossible to double-render something; if the user renders a portion, and then tries to render the whole, they will instead revert the portion. This may be slightly confusing, but it's better than the destructiveness of double-rendering.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Fixed bug: In Firefox (and in Chrome, in theory, but I couldn't make it happen), full-message reverting could fail (instead double-render) if the cursor were outside the rendered block (i.e., at the very beginning, before the wrapper div). This fix involved making full-message render less of a special case: now, if there's no selection, the entire focused element contents are selected. This has a behavioural side-effect that is probably good: It's now impossible to double-render something; if the user renders a portion, and then tries to render the whole, they will instead revert the portion. This may be slightly confusing, but it's better than the destructiveness of double-rendering.

Commit Message: use codecogs for LaTeX rendering by default  Note that the changes in the translation files is mostly just churn. The non-English locales' JSON files weren't properly getting English fallbacks added to them; I did that and sorted the keys on output, to prevent future churn. But the difference in order and whitespace bloated the diff. In the future this shouldn't happen.

Added a favicon to the options page (Chrome was setting it automatically, but Mozilla wasn't). Wired up the math edit field reset button. Fixed some options page styling.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: use codecogs for LaTeX rendering by default  Note that the changes in the translation files is mostly just churn. The non-English locales' JSON files weren't properly getting English fallbacks added to them; I did that and sorted the keys on output, to prevent future churn. But the difference in order and whitespace bloated the diff. In the future this shouldn't happen.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Fixed bug: In Firefox (and in Chrome, in theory, but I couldn't make it happen), full-message reverting could fail (instead double-render) if the cursor were outside the rendered block (i.e., at the very beginning, before the wrapper div). This fix involved making full-message render less of a special case: now, if there's no selection, the entire focused element contents are selected. This has a behavioural side-effect that is probably good: It's now impossible to double-render something; if the user renders a portion, and then tries to render the whole, they will instead revert the portion. This may be slightly confusing, but it's better than the destructiveness of double-rendering.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Fixed bug: In Firefox (and in Chrome, in theory, but I couldn't make it happen), full-message reverting could fail (instead double-render) if the cursor were outside the rendered block (i.e., at the very beginning, before the wrapper div). This fix involved making full-message render less of a special case: now, if there's no selection, the entire focused element contents are selected. This has a behavioural side-effect that is probably good: It's now impossible to double-render something; if the user renders a portion, and then tries to render the whole, they will instead revert the portion. This may be slightly confusing, but it's better than the destructiveness of double-rendering.

Author: Adam Pritchard
Commit Message: Fix #524 and #526: Broken in non-English Thunderbird  A string added in the Firefox 60 fix wasn't copied to the non-English `messages.json` files, which meant that it wasn't in the non-English `strings.properties` and `string.dtd` files. This caused Thunderbird to not load the overlay in Thunderbird, which prevented it from being present in the message window.  To help mitigate this in the future, to some degree, the `i18n.js` script makes sure that all English strings are present in the other languages when creating the the .properties and .dtd files. But I still have to remember to run that script.
